              <fr:mainmatter><html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(X,d)]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(Y,\rho )]]></fr:tex> be <fr:link href="/ca-000K/" title="Metric Space" uri="http://localhost:8000/ca-000K/" display-uri="ca-000K" type="local">Metric Space</fr:link>s. Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> be a family of functions from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>. We say <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> is <html:dfn>Uniformly Equicontinuous</html:dfn> if for any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\in  F]]></fr:tex>, for each <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\varepsilon >0]]></fr:tex> there is a <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta >0]]></fr:tex> such that for any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x,y\in  X]]></fr:tex>, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(x,y)<\delta ]]></fr:tex> then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\rho (f(x),f(y))<\varepsilon ]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
 
   
